'''Erich Schmidt-Leichner''' (14 October 1910 – 17 March 1983) was a [[Germans|German]] lawyer who made a name as a distinguished defense counsel at the [[Nuremberg Trials]] (1945 - 1946). In 1978, he was a defense counsel in the ''Klingenberg Case'' ([[Anneliese Michel]]), where a married couple were accused of [[negligent homicide]] for failing to call a medical doctor during an exorcism of their daughter. 

