[[File:Auburn Gallipoli Mosque.JPG|right|thumb|275px|Gallipoli mosque, Auburn, Sydney.]]
'''Islam in Oceania''' refers to [[Islam]] and [[Muslims]] in [[Oceania]]. By current estimates, there are 620,156 Muslims in Oceania, 476,600 in [[Australia]], 48,151 in [[New Zealand]], 52,520 in [[Fiji]], 6,352 in New Caledonia, 2,200 in [[Papua New Guinea]], 360 in Solomon Islands, 221 in [[Vanuatu]], 110 in [[Tonga]] and tiny numbers in [[Kiribati]] and [[Samoa]].<ref>[http://www.muslimpopulation.com/Oceania/ Muslim Population<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
According to a 2007 article in ''Pacific Magazine'', entitled 'Green Moon Rising', Islam has seen a substantial increase in adherents amongst the peoples of [[Vanuatu]], [[Fiji]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[Papua New Guinea]] and [[New Caledonia]]. There have been thousands of indigenous converts to Islam in [[Melanesia]].<ref>[http://www.pacificmagazine.net/issue/2007/06/29/green-moon-rising Green moon rising] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010082524/http://www.pacificmagazine.net/issue/2007/06/29/green-moon-rising |date=2007-10-10 }}</ref><ref>[http://intellibriefs.blogspot.com/2007/08/pacific-spread-of-islam-in-melanesia.html Pacific: The spread of Islam in Melanesia]</ref>
There are also approximately 400 Muslims in [[Palau]], whose government recently allowed [[Uighur detainees in Guantanamo|a few]] [[Uyghurs]] detained in [[Guantanamo Bay]] to settle in the island nation.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5h0PvMT3xGXLwI-2KwkOThMJToprwD9AK6D1O0 Lawyers: Uighurs agree to go to Palau]</ref>
{{Islam by country}}
==History== Islam has been in some parts of Oceania for at least 400 years (since the 17th century). When the people of [[New Guinea]] traded with China and the Malay empire, in the early 17th century, the presence of Islam was felt in Oceania for the first time.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/country_profiles/3028825.stm BBC NEWS | Asia-Pacific | Country profiles | Timeline: Papua New Guinea<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
Other parts of Oceania did not feel the presence of Islam until the 19th century. For instance, the first Muslims in [[Fiji]] came when Muslim migrants came on a ship bringing indentured labourers to Fiji in 1879. Muslims consisted of 22% of the boarders on ''[[Leonidas (ship)|Leonidas]]'', which was the first such ship.
